f=Engineering/axiom/custom/performance-profiling/SKILL.md · in=performance-profiling axiom's "measure, don't guess" (dev's identity principle, algorithm edition) becomes procedure: before optimizing, measure find actual bottleneck; after optimizing, measure prove change helped; record both, performance claims carry numbers, hopes. It's empirical complement complexity-analysis asymptotics predict, profiling confirms. · p=Engineers optimize wrong thing constantly: clever rewrite function wasn't bottleneck, micro-optimization compiler already did, "obviously faster" change that's slower. Profiling replaces intuition measurement you optimize what profile says hot, you keep change numbers improve. · wu=Triggers: "optimize this," "why slow," "is change faster," "profile it," performance complaint, complexity-analysis said constants dominate, ops's monitoring showing latency regression. · st:/ Protocol=`A performance question \· -> MEASURE FIRST: profile under a realistic workload → find the actual hot spot \· (never optimize before profiling — intuition about bottlenecks is usually wrong) \· -> Analyze: is it algorithmic (complexity-analysis) or constant-factor (implementation)? \· -> Change ONE thing` · in=**Measure before touching anything.** Profile under workload resembles production (realistic realistic distribution). hot spot usually intuition says. Optimizing before profiling effort goes cold code. **Realistic workloads only.** benchmark n=10 production n=10^6 measures wrong regime (complexity-analysis's asymptotics point). Use representative data; note workload record results comparable. **Algorithmic constant-factor.** profile points O(n²) hot loop, that's complexity-analysis's domain (change algorithm). it's O(n) doing expensive work item, it's implementation (allocation, cache misses, redundant work). Fix right layer. **Change one thing, measure again.** Isolate change delta attributable. workload, machine class, conditions comparison across different conditions noise dressed result. **Keep numbers say so.** optimization measured improvement reverted it's added complexity risk nothing (dev's boring-is-a-feature). "It faster" "it faster." **Record evidence.** Before/after numbers, workload, conditions claim reproducible ops's baselines (maintenance-hygiene) reference real figures, folklore. Performance claims without numbers carry rule-0.6 flag. · of=`## Benchmark: [what] — [date] \· Workload: [n, distribution, conditions] \· Profiler: [per stack-profile] \· Hot spot found: [location] \· Type: [algorithmic → complexity-analysis / constant-factor] \· Change: [one thing] \· Before: [metric] \· After: [metric] \· Delta: [%/x] \· Verdict: KEEP / REVERT (no improvement)` · pr=**Measure before optimizing** bottleneck rarely you think., **Realistic workloads** wrong regime measures wrong thing., **Right layer** algorithmic problems need algorithm changes, micro-opts., **One change, attributable delta** comparisons across conditions noise., **Keep measured wins** unmeasured optimization pure risk; revert it., **Claims carry numbers** before/after rule-0.6 flag; folklore. · f=production-like workload available measure best available, label regime gap, treat conclusions provisional; don't extrapolate small-n results large-n silently., Profiler stack use language's basic timing analysis complexity-analysis, labeled lower-fidelity; recommend profiler add stack-profile., Improvement within noise treat improvement (revert); delta smaller run-to-run variance isn't result. · b:with Other Skills=**complexity-analysis** (sibling) predicts; measures. They meet profile shows algorithmic hot spot., **dsa-design-records**: benchmark evidence backs "constants dominate" trade-offs record notes., **ops/maintenance-hygiene**: monitoring baselines production-scale counterpart; latency regression routes profile., **dev**: "measure, don't guess" dev's identity principle; enforcement algorithm layer, unmeasured performance claims carry dev's rule-0.6 flag.